article.headline: Celtics defeat the Nets for third straight time

images.name: Walker Antoine 020407 inline
images.caption: Antoine Walker, right, made a late 3-pointer to help the Celtics win their fourth straight.

article.linkText: Celtics delay Nets' bid for first division title
article.story:
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- The Boston Celtics put the New Jersey Nets' bid for their first NBA division title on hold for a couple of days, and made a little statement in the process. Paul Pierce scored 15 of his 32 points in the fourth quarter and assisted on a big 3-pointer by Antoine Walker as the Celtics beat the Nets 102-90 Sunday night. The victory snapped New Jersey's franchise-record 13-game home winning streak, and also prevented the Nets from clinching the Atlantic Division title. "I really couldn't picture myself watching them celebrate ... against the Boston Celtics," Pierce said. "We're going to delay that one more game. They're going to have to do it against somebody else." The Eastern Conference-leading Nets can capture the division with any combination of Nets wins or Celtics losses totaling two. New Jersey has four regular-season games left, one less than the Celtics. The victory was the fourth straight for Boston. More importantly, it was their third consecutive win over New Jersey this season. "We might have a psychological edge," Pierce said. "This is still the top team in the East. They're a dangerous team. This gives us an edge, knowing we beat them three times if we see them down the line." No one on the Nets was buying that. "We are probably concenred that we haven't played a little better against them, but we don't think we are cursed or that we can't beat the Celtics," Nets center Todd MacCulloch said. "I don't think there's a lot to be learned from this. We learned they seemed to want it more than we did." This Boston win came in a chippy game that featured 63 personal fouls, five individual technicals, three defensive 3-second technicals and the ejection of Celtics backup center Vitaly Potapenko for an altercation involving Kenyon Martin and Jason Kidd. "This game was a statement game," Walker said. "We have to go out there and be physical. Teams look at us and see we don't have a dominating center. We have to show we're not going to back down. We'll fight you to the end with what we have." The Nets did not go meekly either in their attempt to win their first division title since joining the NBA for the 1976-77 season. Trailing by 15 entering the final quarter and with Pierce sitting with five fouls, the Nets rallied behind Kidd and Keith Van Horn. They pulled to 87-86 on Van Horn's 3-pointer with 3:26 to go. Walker hit a 3-pointer off an assist by Pierce with 2:59 left to push the lead to 90-86, and Pierce followed with another 3 at the two-minute mark for a 93-86 lead. "I just stayed with it," Walker said, who hit only one of his previous eight 3-pointers. "They went to a zone after a timeout. Paul drove the middle and found me open. I had the confidence to take that shot." The Nets never got closer than five the rest of the way as Pierce scored 10 of Boston's last 12 points. "We might have gotten caught up in thinking that we were unbeatable at home no matter who it was," MacCulloch said. "They didn't come in here to be walked all over. They came in here to play basketball from the start." The Celtics seemed to take control right after Potapenko was ejected late in the second quarter for throwing a forearm at Martin and slapping away Kidd's hand when he tried to calm him down. Erick Strickland scored the Celtics' next six points, sparking a 17-5 spurt that bridged the end of the half and the opening minutes of the third quarter. Consecutive 3-pointers by Eric Williams and Pierce pushed the lead to 63-44, and Boston seemed ready to pull away. If there was a key to the Nets getting back in the game it came during a 15-second span late in the third quarter when Pierce picked up his fourth and fifth fouls. New Jersey got back in the game with a 15-3 spurt to open the fourth quarter, but the rally fell short. Walker finished with 18 points, and Strickland had 14. Kidd led the Nets with 21, one more than Van Horn. Martin had 16. Game notes
The Nets' loss also prevented them from setting a franchise record with 50 wins. New Jersey was 26-56 last season. ... The loss was only the seventh in 39 home games for New Jersey. ... Pierce was averaging 39 points in his last three games at Continental Airlines Arena. ... The technicals were picked up by Kenny Anderson and two by Potapenko of the Celtics. Martin and Lucious Harris had the Nets' technicals. ... The home loss was the Nets' first since an 85-80 loss to Detroit on Feb. 14 ... Boston is only the third team to win a season series with New Jersey. It is also the only team to beat the Nets twice at the Meadowlands.
